    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-09-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-09-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="568"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d568">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 838.00/1295.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Haitian Minister</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-09-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 10, 1915</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have your two letters dated the 4th and 6th
                    instant, respectively.</p>
                <p>It will, I am sure, be perfectly apparent to you that your two letters and our
                    informal conversations can, under present circumstances, only be considered as
                    having an unofficial character.</p>
                <p>With every desire to preclude the possibility of any future embarrassment, I must
                    again repeat my earnest conviction that the interests of Haiti will best be
                    served by restricting pending negotiations to Port au Prince, exclusively.</p>
                <p>I remain [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
